Memoria
Solo tú
Purpose & context SAGAE (Sistema de Activos y Gestión Administrativa Educativa) is an institutional asset and ticket management system built by SAGAE as sole product owner and deployer, without a technical team. Claude serves as a full professional development team covering security, privacy (Panama's Ley 81 de 2019), testing, documentation, and implementation guidance. Architecture: Backend: SAGAEappsscript.js — Google Apps Script web app connected to Google Sheets Frontend (3 clients): Admin panel (index.html), mobile technician app (SAGAEindexmobile.html), public reporting portal (SAGAEportalreportes.html) Supporting files: manifest.json, sw.js Hosting: Frontends on GitHub Pages; backend deployed as Apps Script web app Data layer: Google Sheets as database, with catalog sheets for departamentos and espacios The institution name is configurable per installation via a Script Property (NOMBREINSTITUCION), exposed through a public config action in doGet — all hardcoded references to specific institutions have been removed (marca blanca). --- Current state Authentication & security redesign (completed, pending end-to-end human testing): Server-side session management via CacheService with 30-minute sliding TTL Password hashing moved exclusively to server (hashPassSeguro / verificarPassword using SHA-256 with salt) PERMSSERVER matrix enforcing role-based access control on every write operation New actions: procesarLogin, sessioncheck, cerrarsesion, crearticketpublico Rate limiting on the public portal (server-side, 20 tickets per 5-minute window) passHash and sessionToken stripped from all API responses All client-side password hashing functions removed from all three frontends CORS workaround (blind POST + GET polling pattern): Confirmed limitation: Google Apps Script doPost responses do not include Access-Control-Allow-Origin headers, making them unreadable by browser fetch() in cors mode Solution: client sends POST in no-cors mode with a requestId; server caches result under that ID for 60 seconds via CacheService; client polls a public GET action (resultado) to retrieve response Applied to: procesarLogin, sessioncheck, cerrarsesion, crearticket_publico, uploadFoto across all three frontends Photo upload (resolved): Root cause was CORS preflight triggered by Content-Type: application/json; fixed by switching to text/plain;charset=utf-8 (CORS-safelisted, avoids preflight) For portal-originated tickets: photo input is locked read-only in admin panel and mobile app (detected via esTicketDePortal() pattern); only a "👁 Ver" button is shown; secondary guard inside abrirDrivePicker() prevents DOM bypass Ticket visibility & UI (completed): Ticket history (historial de seguimiento) now rendered in admin panel modal "Abiertos" tab aggregates all non-closed states (not just literal estado='abierto') Read-only view mode (eye button 👁) for roles without edit permissions Clickable Kanban cards Portal form fields (completed): "Departamento / Área" and "Ubicación" converted from free-text to dynamic <select> elements, fed from live backend catalogs, with ubicaciones filtering based on selected departamento Pending items: End-to-end human testing of full authentication redesign before production deployment XSS sanitization in openTicketSheet (mobile app) Confirmation of five specific legal compliance points under Panama's Ley 81 de 2019 with local legal counsel (personal data in audit history, data retention, etc.) --- On the horizon Legal counsel review of Panama's Ley 81 de 2019 compliance points (cannot be resolved by Claude — must be flagged and referred) Production deployment and live validation of the authentication redesign Potential additional role or permission refinements as real-world usage reveals gaps --- Key learnings & principles Never assume legal compliance: Always flag what requires local legal counsel review; never assert a requirement is met CORS on Apps Script is a hard constraint: doPost responses are browser-unreadable in cors mode; the blind POST + GET polling pattern is the confirmed workaround Apps Script redeployment discipline: Changes only take effect when a new version is created within the existing deployment — "new deployment" changes the /exec URL and must be avoided Security was entirely client-side before redesign: Previous architecture had no server-side RBAC, exposed password hashes to unauthenticated callers, and relied on a single static hardcoded API token — a complete redesign was chosen over patching GitHub Pages .nojekyll: Standard configuration file for SPAs using "Deploy from a branch" pipeline; not application code .nojekyll root cause: Claude was honest that the actual build error log was never obtained, so the causal link to the two failed deployments could not be definitively confirmed --- Approach & patterns SAGAE manually uploads updated files to both GitHub Pages and the Claude.ai project knowledge section to keep the working copy current; Claude has read-only access to project files When only one file changes, all 6 system files must still be delivered together in a single zip, alongside implementation guides in PDF and Word (.docx) format Every session must produce: (1) corrected file zip, (2) step-by-step implementation guide in execution order covering all manual actions outside the chat (GitHub uploads, Apps Script deployment, Script Properties config, etc.), delivered as PDF and .docx — never as markdown SAGAE challenges explanations that conflict with observed behavior and expects honest acknowledgment of uncertainty over confident-sounding guesses Decisions must be documented with clear reasoning --- Tools & resources Backend: Google Apps Script + Google Sheets (CacheService, PropertiesService) Frontend hosting: GitHub Pages (static, "Deploy from a branch" pipeline) File delivery: Zip archives containing all 6 system files + implementation guides in PDF and .docx Legal reference: Panama's Ley 81 de 2019 (data privacy — compliance points must be referred to local legal counsel) Claude.ai project: Used as working file repository (read-only for Claude; SAGAE manually updates files after each session)

